{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1938011201/0682.xml":{"full_text":"2\nCummings Offers\nRemedy for Joker\nIn \u2018Corruption\u2019 Act\nWould Ban Political Contributions After,\nAs Well as Before, FAections\n(1.N.5.) Attorney General Homer S. Cummings today\nrecommended that Congress correct a \u201cjoker\u201d in the corrupt\npractices act by outlawing corporation political contributions\nafter, as well as before, elections.\nWPA Chief\nSees New\nAid Need\nBy FREDERICK N. POLANGIN\n(1.N.5.) Predicting the current\nbusiness decline will reach bottom\nwithin two weeks, a high WPA\nofficial today blasted all hopes the\nAdministration will be able to stay\nwithin the $1,500,000,000 relief ap\npropriation this year.\nSignificant trends along the\nhorizon\u2014depletion of inventories,\nan increase in automobile and tex\ntile production and a stiffening of\nprices\u2014he said, indicate the satu\nration point of wholesale lay-offs\nwill be reached late in January.\nThe upswing, this anonymous\nofficial said, would not be rapid,\nand a deficiency relief appropria\ntion would be necessary.\nThe nation needs a $200,000,000\n\u2022\u2018shot-in-the-arm\" at least, he said,\nto cushion unemployment and\nbolster purchasing power. It was\nexpected that President Roose\nvelt, in a special message, would\nask Congress to supply the addi\ntional funds.\nThis official, disciple of the\n\u201cpump-priming\u2019\u2019 school of thought,\npointed out it would be impossible\nto stay within current relief\nbudgetary limits in view of the\ndrastic drop in unemployment of\nlome 3.000.000. since October.\nAt present, there are approxi\nmately 1,760,000 on the WPA rolls.\nCUFFEY STORY\nIRKS REP. CRAY\n(1.N.5.) The measure of con\ntrol exercised by Senator Guffey\n(D.) of Pennsylvania over the 27\nPennsylvania Democrats in the\nHouse became a subject of contro\nversy today.\nRepresentative Gray (D.) of\nPennsylvania started discussion by\ndeclaring that he would demand\nretraction of a magazine article\nstating that \u201cJoe\u201d Guffey controls\nthe solid block of House votes \u201cand\nknows how to use them.\u201d\n\u201cI do not believe that the\nPennsylvania Democrats in the\nHouse have sunk so low as to\njustify such a statement,\u201d said\nGray. \u201cI want to say for my\nself that it is utterly false. We\nmight be accused of murder or\ntreason but I hope it hasn\u2019t\ncome to a point where anyone\ncan accuse us of being used for\nwhat the Senatdr from Pennsyl\nvania wants.\"\nRepresentative Stack (D.) of\nPhiladelphia, \u201cseconded\u201d the state\nment of Gray while Representa\ntive Bradley (D.) of Pennsylvania\nsaid \u201cthe Senator from Pennsyl\nvania has never tried to control us\nand there is no use denying such\na statement.\u201d\nANIMALS START FIRE\nPORTLAND. Ore., Jan. 12\n(I.N 5 ).\u2014lt begins to look as if\nfire-prevention warnings will have\nto be issued in animal-language in\nPortland. A cat owned by A.\nHinkston knocked over an oil\nlamp, causing its owner to suffer\nburns on both hands. Two days\nlater a goat owned by A. Barclay\nknocked over a candle which its\nowner had set down in the barn\ndoorway, setting fire to a bale of\nhay,\nPublished Dally 1117 R It. N W\nwith Sunday issue as ths Washington\nHerald-Time.\nEditorial and Busines. Phons\nREpablie 1234\nPntersd cs cAe Post O/Fice rasAmpton\nD. C., ru second-ckMS mau mailer,\nEleanor Patterson Editor and Publisher\nWilliam C. Shelton General Manager\nBATES BY CAJtRIEB IX WASHINGTON. DC\nAND SUBURBS\nDally and\nDally Bunday Bunday\nOne Tear I 5 2\u00ab *5 M SlO 40\nSts Months IM s.m S.Jfi\nThroe Mentha 1-30 1.30 too\nOn. Month 45 .45 .90\nOn. Woafc IB .IB .20\nBATES BY MAIL TOR VIRGINIA. MARYLAND\nWIST VIRGINIA AND NORTH CAROLINA\nDaily and\nDally Bunday Bunday\nOm Yser SC-M M 00 111 00\nSix Month. I W I M Y oo\nfbrM ktaitk* I.M I.K I SO\nOa\u00ab H*aU 110\nmm iTATaa can ad* and mkxico\nDaily and\nDally Bunday Bunday\nOne You ST M r.M 115 W\nSix Month. S.M I.M T M\nThree Martha LN I.M it*\nOne Meth M.M I.M\nAH MAIL SUBSCRIPTIONS PAYABIaB 1\nIN ADVANCE 1\nTtltphont REpublie 1234\nHe submitted a bill to Congress\nwith a recommendation that it be\nenacted into law.\nEXPLAINS LAW\nUnder present law. Cummings\nexplained, corporations are pro\n'hibited from making political con\ni tributions before elections. How\never. he said, they can make con\ntributions after elections to aid\nin meeting campaign deficits.\nI He notified Congress recently\nthat he would recommend amend\nment of the corrupt practices act.\nin informing Representative Snell\n(R.), New York, that he found no\nviolation of law in the sale of the\nrecent Democratic campaign\nbooks to corporations.\nThe Attorney General explained\nthat the Federal corrupt practices\nact specifically prohibits contribu\ntions by national banks or other\ncorporations chartered by the\nFederal Government.\nFINES PROVIDED\nUnder present law a corpora\ntion making a campaign contri-J\nbution before election is subject\nto a $5,000 fine. Any officer of a\ncorporation consenting to such a\ngift is subject to a fine of SI,OOO\n!or one year\u2019s imprisonment, or\nboth.\nIndustrialists\nTo Parley\n(Cont*nued from Page 1)\ningham. Mass.: R. R. Deupree.\npresident, the Procter and Gamble\nCompany, Cincinnati, Ohio; Wil\nliam C. Dickerman, president,\nAmerican Locomotive Company,\nNew York: \"'homas A. Dines, pre-s\nident, the U. S. National Bank.\nDenver, Colo.; Gano Dunn, presi\ndent, J. G. White Engineering\nCorporation, New York; Col. Rob\nert G. Elbert, retired. New York.\nFAHEY TO BE THERE\nDr. W. Y. Elliott, department of\ngovernment, Harvard University;\nJohn H. Fahey, chairman. Fed\neral Home Loan Bank Board:\nLincoln Filene, chairman of\nboard. William Filene\u2019s Sons Co.,\nBoston, Mass.; T. Austin Finch,\npresident, Thomasville Chair Co.,\nThomasville, N. C.; Robert V.\nFleming, president, the Riggs Na\ntional Bank, Washington D. C.;\nJames F. Fogarty, president, the\nNorth American Co., New York;\nM. B. Folsom, treasurer, Eastman\nKodak Co., Rochester, N. Y.;\nClarence Francis, president, Gen\neral Foods Corp., New York; H.\nB. Friele, vice president, the Nakat\nPacking Corp., Seattle, Wash.\nHARRIMAN ASKED\nRolland J. Hamilton, president,\nAmerican Radiator Co., New\nYork; W. A. Harriman (chairman\nof the council) chairman of the\nboard, Union Pacific Railroad\nCo.; Henry H. Heimann, executive\nmanager. National Association\nCredit Men, New York; Charles\nR. Hook, president, the American\nRolling Mill Co., Middletown,\nOhio; Frank C. Jones, president,\nthe Okonite Co., Passaic, N. J.;j\nWilliam A. Julian, treasurer of the\nUnited States; H. P. Kendall, I\npresident, the Kendall Co., Bos\nton; Fred I. Kent, treasurer, Na\ntional Industrial Conference\nBoard, New York; De Lancey\nKountze, chairman of board, De\nvoe and Reynolds Co.. Inc., New\nYork; Morris E. Leeds, president,\u2019\nLeeds and Northrup Co., Philadel\nphia; Dr. C. K. Leith, professor of;\ngeology, University of Wisconsin.\nMadison, Wis.; Paul W. Litchfield,\npresident, the Goodyear Tire\nRubber Co., Akron; Earl M. Mc-\nGowin, vice president, W. T.\nSmith Lumber Co., Inc., Chap\nman. Ala.: George H. Mead, presi\ndent. Mead Corpn., Dayton. Ohio;\nKermit Roosevelt, president,\nRoosevelt Steamship Co., Inc.,\nNew York: George A. Sloan. New\nYork; E. T. Stannard, president,\nKennecott Copper Corp., New\ni York; E. R. Stettinius, jr\u201e chair\nman, finance committee, U. S.\nSteel Corp., New York; R. Douglas\niI Stuart, vice president, Quaker\nOats Co., Chicago: Walter C.\nTeagle, chairman of the board,\n1 Standard Oil Co. (N. J.), New\n'York,\nPope Has Scant Hope of Peace\nWith Reich; Duce May Act\nVATICAN CITY. Jan. 12 (1.N.5.).\u20141n\nhis longest speech in years, Pope Pius to\nday saw little hope for a Catholic-Nazi\nreconciliation; yet in diplomatic quarters\nit was believed that Premier Mussolini\nplanned intervention to bring about friend\nly relations between Germany and the Holy\nSee.\nThe Pope launched into his latest criti\ncism of the Reich in a sudden appeal to\nseveral thousand Italian propaganda\nworkers who are shortly leaving on a mis\nsion to Germany.\n\u201cAct as firm disciples of the Christian\nfaith!\u201d he urged.\nIn spite of the tenor of the Pope\u2019s re\nmarks. the belief that II Duce planned some\naction on behalf of the Church grew out of\nhis speech Sunday, when, talking to a\ngroup of bishops and priests, he made re\npeated warm references of friendship for\nthe Holy See.\n\u201cFrom my post at the helm of the bark\nof St. Peter's.\u201d said the 80-year-old Pope,\n\u201cI cannot fail to see visions descending\nJobs Program Mapped\nFor Senate by Rail Head\n(Continued from Page 1)\nas a means of distributing \u201cwelled\nup\u201d purchasing power.\nA more prosperous railroad in-j\ndustry would stimulate business, in\ncrease employment and serve to\ncheck the recession, Pelley de-\ndared.\nTestifying that most railroads 1\nhave practically abandoned new\nequipment programs and that\n106,000 employes have been sev\nered from the pay roll since last j\nyear, Pelley said:\n\u201cWhen their business is good,\nthe railroads buy and utilize 1\nmore than 20 per cent of the\ncoal output of the United States, i\nnearly 20 per cent of the fuel\noil output and the timber cut,\nmore than 15 per cent of iron\nand steel output and apperciable I\nproportions of other heavy I\ngoods, such as cement, stone,\ngravel and the like.\n\u201cIf their traffic and revenues i\nreturn to more nearly normal I\nlevels than at present, their an\nnual equipment program could\neasily contemplate the installa-\ntion of 2,000 new locomotives,\nand 100,000 new freight cars per\nyear.\u201d\nIn 1937, the railroads Installed\nless than 500 locomotives and;\n75,000 new freight cars, Pelley\nsaid:\nJOBS BAROMETER\nHe asserted that for every man\ndirectly employed by the railways\nin their own operations, one\nman is employed by other indus-\nI tries in the production and distri\nbution of \u201cthe 70,000 different\nkinds of articles purchased and\nused by the railways.\u201d\n\u201cIt follows then that when\nrailways lay off men, men also\nlose employment in other in\ndustries,\u201d Pelley added.\n\u201cRailway employment today\nis less by some 75,000 men than\nit was a year ago. If these men\nwere brought back to work in\nrailway shops and on the tracks,\nproduction of materials they\nwould utilize would give employ\nment to another 75,000 men out\nside the railway industry, thus\nsupplying reemployment to a\ntotal of not less than 150,000\nmen.\u201d\nPelley made no mention of re\nj cent freight and passenger rate in\ncreases granted to some of the car\nj riers by the ICC, and pending ap\nplications for additional increases,\nas he forecast a gloomy outlook.\nTELLS OF RECESSION\n\u201cRailway traffic during the\nfirst nine months of 1937\nshowed a gratifying increase\nover the corresponding months\nI of 1936, then turned sharply\ndownward during the remainder\nof the year, and is still at a\nI very low level,\u201d he saia. \u201cRev\nenue followed the trend of traf\nfic. while net earnings showed\nan even greater relative de\ncline.\n\u201cAs a result of this decline,\u201d\nPelley added, \u201crailway manage\nments found it imperative to in\nstitute immediate and drastic\ni economies.\u201d\nDuring the last three months of\ni 1937 the business outlook for the\ncarriers brought the employment\naverage down to 3 per cent below\n5 that of 1936 despite the fact that\nr for the first nine months of 1937\nemployment was \u201cconsistently\ngreater than in 1936,\u201d Pelley said\ni \u201cThis decline was an acceler\nating one,\u201d he added, \u201camount-\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, WEDNESDAY, JANUARY 12, 1938\nBy FRANK GERVASI\nIng to 32.000 men in November,\nand 73..00 men in December.\u201d\nPURCHASES SLASHED\nPurchase of fuel, material and\nsupplies during the first nine\nmonths of 1937 were 30 per cent\ngreater than the corresponding\npurchases in 1936,\u201d Pelley said,\n\u201cwhile purchases of the final\nthree months in 1937 were 4 per\ncent less than in 1936.\u201d\nEquipment purchases and in\nstallations were also heavy dur\ning the first nine months of 1938,\nbut declined rapidly during the\nremainder of the year, he said,\nadding:\n\u201cIn fact, new orders were neg\nligible in the last quarter of\n1937, and the units of equip\nment delivered in that period\nwere those ordered some months\npreviously, under contracts\nwhich the railways were legally\nbound to carry out.\u201d\nOPPOSES WORK SHARING\nReplying to questions by Seha\n[tor Byrnes <D.) of South Carolina,\nj chairman of the committee, Pelley\nfrowned on an extensive \u201cshare\nj the work\u201d program to take up the\nunemployment slack in the rail\nroad industry.\n\u201cIn my opinion all that could\nbe done along that line has been\ndone in the past,\u201d Pelley said.\n\u201cAnd it proved to be very in\nefficient.\u201d\nPelley said the railways could go\nfarward with a wide construction\nand reemployment program if the\nICC would approve their applica\ntion for increased freight rates.\n\u201cThat is the only thing that\nwe can see to do at the pres\nent,\u201d he added.\nDEFENDS PROPOSED RISE\n\u201cDo you think that higher\nfreight rates could be paid,\nespecially in the agricultural\ndistricts?\u201d asked Byrnes.\n\u201cYes, sir,\u201d Pelley replied\npromptly. \u201cEven if the ICC\nwere to grant the increases we\nhave applied for the rates\nwould not be as high as they\nwere in 1930.\n\u201cIf the increase is granted it\nwill open our purchasing doors,\nand we will begin buying and\nthe general situation will be im\nproved.\u201d\nPROBLEMS OF NEGROES\ni \u201cThe Problems of Negroes in\nWashington as Seen by a Public\n-.Family Agency\u201d will be discussed\nby Miss M. Alice Hill, director of\nthe public assistance division of\nthe Department of Public Wei\nfare, before the Churchmen\u2019s\nLuncheon Club at the Twelfth\nStreet Branch Y. M, C. A. to\nmorrow at 11:45 a. m. This\nmarks the beginning of a series\nof discussions on community\nproblems.\nFiremen Push\n5-Day Week\nI Early action on a bill to estab\nlish a five-day 60-hour week in the\nlocal fire department was asked\nj today by the City Firefighters As\nsociation in a letter to the House\nDistrict Committee.\nJ Denying that enactment of the\ne i measure would cost the District\nt $500,000 a year, the association\nK stated it could be put into opera\n,t tion with no additional cost \"by\n7; proper reassignment and utiliza-\n1 tion of certain membei c of the\ny nonfire-fighting division of the\ndepartment and possible consoli\ndation of forces in certain engine\nhouses.\u201d\nbeyond the Alps which seem menacing, or\nat least nebulous \u2014and behind which there\ndoes not seem to be a ray of sunshine.\u201d\nSorrowfully referring to alleged Nazi\npersecution of the Catholic Church, the\nPope asserted that priests should accom\npany the Italian workers into Germany to\nprovide spiritual assistance against any\nanti-Catholic onslaught by the Nazis.\nIn marked contrast to the Pontiff\u2019s com\nments on Germany was his praise of the\nItalo-Vatican accord.\nHe said he was \u201csupremely consoled\u201d by\nthe fact that Italy had kept faith.\n\u201cWe do not doubt that the word of this\nhighly sovereign engagement will be\nkept,\u201d he said, \u201cand that benediction will\nbe found in abundance.\u201d\nAnother favorable sign seen here was the\nexchange of friendly expressions between\nReichsfuehrer Hitler and the Papal Nuncio,\nMsgr. Cesare Orsenigo, at the diplomatic\nreception in Berlin yesterday, when both\nappealed for reconciliation.\nDR. FISHER SEES\nROOSEVELT RUIN\nNEW YORK, Jan. 12 (1.N.5.).\n\u201cUnless the present deflation is\nsoon remedied, it will probably\nruin Roosevelt.\u201d\nThat was the opinion today of\nDr. Irving Fisher, professor\nemeritus of economics at Yale\nUniversity.\n\u201cTo cure the recession\u201d\nFisher told the New York Uni\nversity Economics Society last\nnight, \u201cwhat is needed is\ngreater confidence to set the\nwheels of money turning again\nand\u2014more money.\n\u201cAt present our money sup\nply is a football kicked around\nby many players including the\nFederal Reserve Board, the\nTreasury and the banks.\u201d\nRecalling that he warned\nPresident Hoover that either de\nflation or inflation would ruin\nhim, he asserted: \u201cDeflation came\nand did ruin him.\u201d He added,\n\u201cIt will probably ruin Roosevelt.\u201d\nBroker Cleared\nIn Stock Charge\nNEW YORK, Jan. 12 (1.N.5.).\nMoe Platt, New York broker and\npresident of the Backbone Gold\nMining Company, today was re\nlieved of the necessity of going\nto the United States district court\nin Pittsburgh, where he and five\nothers face charges of conspiracy\nand use of the mails to violate the\nSecurities Exchange Act.\nIn refusing to order Platt\u2019s re\nmoval and in directing Platt\u2019s re\nlease, U. S. Commissioner Martin\nC. Epstein ruled in Brooklyn Fed\neral Court that there had not been\nenough evidence presented to him\nto indicate Platt had been involved\nin a crime. The charges grew out\nof alleged manipulation of over\nthe-counter securities in 1935 and\n1936.\nFirst Lady Hostess\nTo Paralysis Foes\nWomen leaders in the campaign\nto unify and put on nation-wide\nbasis efforts to stamp out infantile\nparalysis were guests of Mrs. Roose\nvelt this afternoon at a White\nHouse tea.\nThe First Lady discussed with\nher guests a proposed program of\nfund-raising for the newly-organ\nized National Foundation for In\nfantile Paralysis, and in a country\ni wide broadcast will describe worn\n-1 en\u2019s part in the campaign.\nSuspect Identified\nIn Holdup Assault\nARLINGTON COUNTY COURT\nHOUSE, Va\u201e Jan. 12.\u2014John West,\ncolored, 26, of Rosslyn, was behind\njail bars today charged with the\nassault and robbery of William\nLoveless, auto-railer operator, on\nNew Year\u2019s Eve.\nLoveless was held up at Green\nValley, a colored settlement,\nyanked from the auto-railer,\nrobbed of sls and left beaten in\nthe underbrush. Loveless iden\ntified West as his assailant.\nCapt. Loul* Roache. Last of the Old-\nTime Missiaalppl River Captain*. Con\ntinues ill* Account of the Men and\nWomen Who Gambled Their Adventu\nrou* Way in the Good Old Day* Aboard\n1 Boat* and Aloni the Shore* of the Mie\n*l**lppl River nod It* Tributaries. He\nTell* How a Notorlou* Gambler Out\nwitted Hl* Cheating Opponent* and\nHow Fortune* Were Won and Lost on\nthe Flip of a Card. Don\u2019t Mia* Thi*\nI Thrilling Double Page illustrated Fea-\nI tore in The American Weekly, with\nI Sunday'a Washington Herald-Time*.\nOPINION SPLIT\nIN SENATE OVER\nITEM VETO PLAN\nHouse Rider Confers\nBlanket Powers\n(1.N.5.) Action of the House, in\nattaching an \u201citem veto\u201d amend\nment to the $1,400,000,000 inde\npendent offices appropriation bill,\nevoked mixed comment in the Sen-'\nate today.\nA judiciary subcommittee set\nJanuary 21 for a public hearing\non a resolution by Senator Van\ndenberg (R.) of Michigan, to give\nthe President power to veto items\nin appropriation bills by constitu\ntional amendment.\nDecision of the House to grant\nthe power by legislation, rather\nthan through amendment to the\nConstitution, found the issue di\nvided between the Senate Appro\npriations and Judiciary commit\ntees.\nHOUSE BILL IN SENATE\nThe former now has before it\nthe House bill, whereas the Judi\nciary Committee is considering the\nconstitutional amendment route.\nThe authority was conferred\nunder a rider added to the $1,500,\n000,000 independent offices supply\nbill passed by the House yesterday\nIn effect, the rider proposed by\nRepresentative Woodrum (D.) of\nVirginia, would give the President\n\u201citem veto\u201d power. Similar au\nthority is asked in constitutional\namendment resolutions pending in\nboth the Senate and House.\nMAY BECOME ISSUE\nThe House, caught by surprise\nand with but a handful of mem\nbers present, adopted the rider by\na voice vote with but few pro- 1\ntests. The provision, however,\nmay become a major issue in the\nSenate on the ground it is a new\nsurrender of congressional power\nto the Chief Executive. 1\nPresident Roosevelt asked for\nsuch authority in his budget mes-\nsage, in which he estimated a defi- 1\ncit of $950,000,000 next year.\nUnder terms of the rider he could\neither eliminate or reduce Govern-\nment activities, to further reduce\nthe deficit.\nThe amendment \"provides:\nTEXT OF AMENDMENT\n\u201cThe President is authorized\nto eliminate or reduce by execu-\ntive order, in whole or in part,\nany appropriation or appropria\ntions made by this act, or any\nother act or joint resolution,\nwhenever after investigation he\nshall find and declare that such\naction will aid in balancing the\nbudget or in reducing the public\ndebt and that the public interest\nwill be served thereby.\u201d\nThe House passed the economy\nplan today, authorizing blanket\npower to the President to slash\nindividual items in appropriation\nbills as an aid in balancing the\nbudget.\nBank Bandit Pair\nTaken by G-Men\n(I.NJS.) Arrest at Houston,\nTex., of Hugh Gant, 37, ind his\nbrother-in-law, Alva Hutt, 36,\nsought in connection with eight\nSouthern bank robberies, was an\nnounced today by the Federal Bu\nreau of Investigation.\nThe bureau said the pair, and\nMiss Alene Bledsoe, 20, friend of\nHunt, surrendered without re\nsistance, though both men were\ncarrying .45 caliber automatic\npistols.\nWoman Injured\nBy Automobile\nMrs. Georgie Goodchild, 61, of\n33 Michigan Ave. N. was seri\nously injured today when she was\nstruck in front of her home by\nan automobile driven, police re\nported, by William G. Breen of\nOxon Hill, Md. She is in Sibley\nHospital with fractures of the left\nleg and wrist. Breen was released\nin SSOO bond pending the outcome\nof her injuries.\nToday In\nCongress\nSENATE\nMeets at noon.\nResumes debate on antilynching\nbill.\nUnemployment Committee con\ntinues hearings.\nConferees consider housing and\nfarm bills.\nHOUSE\nMeets at noon.\nConsiders bills on the Wednes\nday calendar. Interstate Commerce\nhas the call.\nDistrict subcommittee considers\nDistrict tax program.\nAppropriations subcommittees\nconsider Justice and D. C. supply\nbills.\nTelepAone RE publie 1234\nAnti-Lynch Bill\nFoes Confident of\nVictory in Senate\nBailey and King Blast Measure; Connally\nSees Strength Growing\nBy ARTHUR HACHTEN\n(1.N.5.), Senate opponents of the antilynching bill today\npredicted victory in the bitter fight that has found the South\nin a titanic struggle with the North.\nAs the sixth day of debate on\nthe measure started in the Sen\nate, with Senators Bailey (D.),\nNorth Carolina, and King\u2019(D.),\nUtah, delivering blasts against the\nmeasure, Senator Tom Connally\n(D.) of Texas, declared:\nGAINING STRENGTH\n\u201cWe are getting stronger all\nthe time. We are prepared to\nhold the Senate floor until\nChristmas if necessary to pre\nvent a vote on this vicious, sec\ntional vote-getting bill.\u201d\nDemocratic Leader Barkley said\nno moves would be made this week\nfor night sessions to wear out op\nponents of the bill and hasten a\nvote.\n\u201cI don\u2019t believe the opponents\nof the bill have many speakers\nleft to prevent a vote,\u201d said\nBarkley. \u201cWe are going to let\nthe debate run along for a while\nand see what happens. I think\nwe will get a vote on the bill\nsome time next week.\u201d\nHe said there had not been\nmuch filibustering against the bill\nsince it was brought up last\nThursday.\n\u201cThe debate for the most part\nhas been legitimate and I see\nno need for night sessions,\u201d he\nsaid.\nSPLIT IS FEARED\nOther Democrats privately\nvoiced concern over what they\ntermed sharp speeches by Senators\nHarrison (D.) of Mississippi and\nBrynes (D.) of South Carolina,\npredicting a serious split in the\nDemocratic party as a result of the\nanti-lynching bill.\nPossibility that the anti-lynch\ning issue may be carried into the\nnext presidential race, if the meas\nure becomes a law, was weighed.\nDemocratic Senators having presi\ndential aspirations and supporting\nthe anti-lynching bill, will have\nlining up Southern dele\ngates for the nominating conven\ntion, Harrison stated. Likewise,\nDemocratic Senators aspiring\nto appointment to the Supreme\nCourt, also will find opposition\nfrom Southern States if they vote\nfor the bill.\nMeanwhile, scant progress was\nbeing made toward reaching an\nagreement In the Senate-House\nconference on the housing bill. The\nfarm bill also was locked in confer\nence. Enemies of the anti-lynch\ning bill said they will be able to\nhold that measure before the Sen\nate housing or farm measure is re\nported.\nSNUFF PRACTICE\n\u201cTaking snuff\u201d through the\nnose was a fashionable practice\nduring the seventeenth and eigh\nteenth centuries.\nROSS SPINET=z\nlu K\n\u25a1j\nco\nlu\nYes, we all like nice tiling* and wken it\ncome* to (electing a conaole piano, tke\nckoice i* invariably a Betsy Ros* Spinet.\nDesigned and built by Lester Craftsmen,\nits swift toueb is incomparable and its tone\ni* full-voiced and A W\u00a3EK\nstrong. See it 0<I \u00abY X PAYS\nor mail tbe coupon. Flu. Budg.t Chargp\nFRICZD $243 UF\nLtittr\u2014Half-Ctntury of Fine Piano Building\ni F. A. NORTH PIANO CO.* Inc.\n1231 G St. N. W.\nPlease send catalogue\nName\nAddress\nU. S. Builders\nOpen Parley\nIn Capital\nA plan to swell the nation\u2019s\nhome construction industry thia\nyear to a two billion dollar volume\nwill be further discussed by build\ners, architects and developers at\ntending the Home and Commun\nity Building Association convert\ntion at the Washington Hotel.\nLaunched yesterday by Dan A.\nLoftus, president of the organiza\ntion, the proposal envisages a na\ntionally cooperative movement,\namong those associated with the\nhome building industry.\nLoftus asserted such activity\nwould set up an industry to which\n$30,000,000,000 could be madp\navailable in loans from banks, in\nsurance companies and building\nand loan associations.\nHe urged those who have de\nvoted their activity to selling lots,\nto concentrate on the building of\nhomes. In this way, he said, the\nmovement would gain stimulus.\nHorace Russell, general counsel\nof the Federal Home Loan Bank,\nsaid approximately $4,000,000,000\na year is needed by the American\npeople to be extended in long term\ncredits for home financing.\nSLAYER OF WIFE\nTRAPPED BY SON\nPUEBLO, Col., Jan. 12 (1.N.5.).\nTrapped by his own son, Everett\nHughes, 52, today awaited ar\nraignment on a charge of mur\ndering his wife.\nHughes confessed yesterday\nand led officers to the shallow\ngrave in which he had buried the\nbody beside a lonely road. He\nsaid he killed her when she\nthreatened to divorce him.\nC. R. Hughes, his son, became\nsuspicious when he received a\npoorly typed letter, purportedly\nfrom his mother. Knowing her\nto be an, expert typist, he re\nturned from his Government post\nin Denver and founo bloodstains\nin his home. He notified author\nities.\nSHIPPER DEAD\nST. JOHN, N. B\u201e Jan. 12 (I.N.\nS.). \u2014Capt. Robert Rankine, of\nGlasgow, who came here as a\nDonaldson line shipper 3C years\nago, is dead of pneumonia, con\ntracted on a voyage from Glasgow,","height":"25928","width":"20400"}}
